Since $ABCDEFGH$ is a regular octagon, we can divide it into 8 congruent isosceles triangles, each with base 2 and vertex angle $\frac{360^\circ}{8}=45^\circ$.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E, F, G, H;

A = dir(22.5);
B = dir(67.5);
C = dir(112.5);
D = dir(157.5);
E = dir(202.5);
F = dir(247.5);
G = dir(292.5);
H = dir(337.5);

draw(A--B--C--D--E--F--G--H--cycle);
draw(A--D);
draw(A--G);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, NE);
label("$C$", C, E);
label("$D$", D, SE);
label("$E$", E, S);
label("$F$", F, SW);
label("$G$", G, W);
label("$H$", H, NW);
[/asy]

Consider $\triangle ADG$.  The height of this triangle is equal to the length of an apothem of the octagon, and the base of the triangle is $AG = 2 + 2 = 4$.  To find the apothem, consider one of the isosceles triangles.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E, F, G, H;

A = dir(22.5);
B = dir(67.5);
C = dir(112.5);
D = dir(157.5);
E = dir(202.5);
F = dir(247.5);
G = dir(292.5);
H = dir(337.5);

draw(A--B--C--D--E--F--G--H--cycle);
draw(A--D);
draw(A--G);
draw(A--(A + dir(45)));

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, NE);
label("$C$", C, E);
label("$D$", D, SE);
label("$E$", E, S);
label("$F$", F, SW);
label("$G$", G, W);
label("$H$", H, NW);
label("$2$", (A + B)/2, NE);
label("$a$", (A + (A + dir(45)))/2, NW);
[/asy]

Let $a$ be the length of the apothem.  The apothem bisects the base of the isosceles triangle, so the apothem is the altitude to the base.  The apothem also bisects the vertex angle of the isosceles triangle, so the two smaller triangles formed are 45-45-90 triangles.  Thus, the length of the apothem is $a = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \cdot 2 = \sqrt{2}$.

The area of $\triangle ADG$ is $\frac{1}{2} \cdot 4 \cdot \sqrt{2} = \boxed{2\sqrt{2}}$.

